[LL_WEBREPORT_EXITIF (expression) [:USECASE] /]

(expression) Format:
"parmA" <operator> "parmB" <optional clauses>
Causes the processing of rows to stop when a condition is met. If the specified expression evaluates to TRUE, then no more rows will be included in the output. The current row being processed is not included if the expression evaluates to true. For example:

[LL_WEBREPORT_EXITIF "[LL_REPTAG_ROWNUM /]" == "10" /]
In this example, rows numbered 1 to 9 will be output but not row 10. Note: this is the only conditional tag where it is safe to use the ROWNUM tag in an expression. This tag only works in the row section i.e. between the [LL_WEBREPORT_STARTROW /] and [LL_WEBREPORT_ENDROW /] tags.

Notes:

(See also [LL_WEBREPORT_INCLUDEIF /] or Advanced Notes on Logical Expressions for more detail)

This tag does not change the TOTALROWS tag which will always reflect the number of rows that were actually available from the database table. To access the number of rows which are actually returned (i.e. that pass the conditional test), the ACTUALROWS tag should be used. See the specific syntax information for these tags.
ParmA and parmB can be either text or another report tag (all other tags are resolved first).
The parameters must be enclosed inside double quotation marks.
See the section on Logical Expressions for a list of Operators.
Additional, optional clauses are added using one of the following operators:
AND (logical AND)
&& (aternative AND)
OR (logical OR)
|| (alternative OR)
Expression Examples:

[LL_WEBREPORT_EXITIF "[LL_REPTAG_&var1 /]" != "[LL_REPTAG=DATAID /]" /]
[LL_WEBREPORT_EXITIF "[LL_REPTAG_ROWNUM /]" == "101" /]
[LL_WEBREPORT_EXITIF "[LL_REPTAG=dataid /]" NOTCHILDOF "[LL_REPTAG_&rootid /]" OR "[LL_REPTAG=parentid /]" NOTCHILDOF "[LL_REPTAG_&rootid /]" /]
		
[LL_WEBREPORT_FOR VAR:<varName> DATA:<data> /]
   [LL_REPTAG_%<varName> CURRENTVAL /]
[LL_WEBREPORT_ENDFOR /]
This tag is used to loop over a collection of data. Valid collections include Lists, RecArrays, Assocs, Records and Strings.

The tag has two required parameters:

Parameter	Purpose
DATA:<collection>	The collection to iterate, which can be a List, RecArray, Assoc, Record, or String.
VAR:<iterator>	The looping variable name. This variable becomes visible in the looping block. A second variable named <iterator>_index is also defined, which is the index of the element.
Examples

To output the elements of a list:

[LL_WEBREPORT_FOR DATA:{'apple','pear','orange'} VAR:"value" /]
   [LL_REPTAG_%value_index CURRENTVAL /] - [LL_REPTAG_%value CURRENTVAL /]<br>
[LL_WEBREPORT_ENDFOR /]
returns:

1 - apple
2 - pear
3 - orange
For loops can also contain other for loops. For example, the following will output each field in each row of the data source:

[LL_WEBREPORT_FOR DATA:[LL_REPTAG_DATASOURCE /] VAR:i /]
   [LL_WEBREPORT_FOR DATA:[LL_REPTAG_%i CURRENTVAL TOLIST /] VAR:j /]
      [LL_REPTAG_%j CURRENTVAL /]
   [LL_WEBREPORT_ENDFOR /]
[LL_WEBREPORT_ENDFOR /]
Optionally include the [LL_WEBREPORT_BREAK /] subtag to break out of a for loop. For example:

[LL_WEBREPORT_FOR DATA:[LL_REPTAG=DataID CAT:RAW /] VAR:Category /]
   [// Loop through the category data until we find the "Fruit" category
   [LL_WEBREPORT_IF "[LL_REPTAG_%Category CURRENTVAL ASSOC:DisplayName /]" == "Fruit" /]
      [// Display something
      This document contains the Fruit category.
      [// Break out of the FOR loop
      [LL_WEBREPORT_BREAK /]
   [LL_WEBREPORT_ENDIF /]
[LL_WEBREPORT_ENDFOR /]
See also: LL_REPTAG_DATASOURCE   CURRENTVAL   TOLIST   

		
[LL_WEBREPORT_FORCEUTF8 /]
This tag forces a UTF-8 Byte Order Marker (BOM) to be added to the beginning of the output from the WebReport. The BOM is made of the hex characters: #FE #BB #BF. Some client applications may require this marker to correctly handle UTF-8 content.

		
[LL_WEBREPORT_FORMPARSEOFF /]
This tag is only used when working with WebReports in forms (via the WR Power View option in form templates). When this tag is included in a WR Power View, the normal WebForms tag parsing code will not be invoked and instead a simplified parser (built into the WebReports engine) is used. This simple parser will handle subsitution of WebForms tag syntax (such as [LL_FormTag_... /] type tags) but will not handle any LOOP tags or any form tags associated with WebForms loops. This tag also disables the WebForms feature that automatically sets HTML SELECT and CHECKBOX form fields with default values. In some cases this feature of WebForms can be problematic and may actually fail when non-standard HTML is used for fields like SELECT statements. In these situations the FORMPARSEOFF tag should be used to prevent any conflict with the WebForms code. For more information see WebReports Power View.

		
[LL_WEBREPORT_IF (expression) [:USECASE] /]
[LL_WEBREPORT_ELSEIF (expression) [:USECASE] /] (optional)
[LL_WEBREPORT_ELSE /] (optional)
[LL_WEBREPORT_ENDIF /]

(expression) Format:
"parmA" <operator> "parmB" <optional clauses>
If a condition is met then include the contents in the output. Anything between the IF and ENDIF tags will only be included if the specified condition evaluates to true. If an ELSE clause is included then everything between the ELSE tag and the ENDIF tag are included if the specified condition evaluates to false. This tag differs from the INCLUDEIF tag in that this structure allows selected parts of the row to be conditionally included or excluded. This tag can be used anywhere in the Reportview. When including or excluding the whole row section always use the LL_WEBREPORT_INCLUDEIF tag rather than IF as this will give better performance.

See the section on Advanced Notes on Logical Expressions for a list of Operators. For more examples of expressions see the LL_WEBREPORT_INCLUDEIF examples.

See also: LL_WEBREPORT_EXITIF   LL_WEBREPORT_INCLUDEIF   

		
[LL_WEBREPORT_INCLUDEDISTINCT "<distinct key>" /]

Distinct Key:
The distinct key can be either: a column name, a column number or a WebReports Tag/Sub-tag combination.
Used to limit the rows returned by the WebReport so that only unique key values are returned.

The "Distinct Key" value specifies which column (or WebReports data tag) should be unique. Only rows that result in a unique value for this key will be included from the data source. Any rows that result in the same value for the specified key will be discarded.

Notes:

The matching for Distinct Keys is Case Insensitive
Where there are rows with duplicate keys, the first row in the current order is kept and all subsequent rows are discarded
The order of rows used for duplicate comparison is based on the original data source order and any WebReport SORT tags that are included in the row section
The filtering of rows using this tag occurs before other row filter tags such as LL_WEBREPORT_INCLUDEIF, LL_WEBREPORT_EXITIF and LL_WEBREPORT_INCLUDERANGE.
For example, given the following data set:

DataID	FruitName
12345	Apple
12346	Orange
12347	Apple
12348	Banana
12349	Orange
12350	APPLE
If the row section had an LL_WEBREPORT_INCLUDEDISTINCT filter such as:

[LL_WEBREPORT_INCLUDEDISTINCT "FruitName" /]
This would result in only rows that had a unique value in the "FruitName" column:

DataID	FruitName
12345	Apple
12346	Orange
12348	Banana
The same result would occur if the column number 1 was used, e.g.: [LL_WEBREPORT_INCLUDEDISTINCT "1" /] This tag also supports the use of WebReports tag/sub-tag combinations. For example, using the original data example and this tag:

[LL_WEBREPORT_INCLUDEDISTINCT "[LL_REPTAG=FruitName DECODE:Banana:apple /]" /]
The following rows would remain after the filter was executed:

DataID	FruitName
12345	Apple
12346	Orange
In this example, the WebReports sub-tag DECODE converts any data that matches the string "Banana" to "apple". As the data value "Apple" already exists in a previous row, the row that normally has the value "Banana" in this column is no longer unique. This feature is most useful when sub-tags such as NODEINFO and or CAT are used to translate dataid fields into other related data values that might not be unique.

		
[LL_WEBREPORT_INCLUDEIF (expression) [:USECASE] /]

(expression) Format:
"parmA" <operator> "parmB" <optional clauses>
Used to determine whether or not a row of data will be included. If this condition is TRUE, then the whole row will be included, otherwise the whole row will be ignored. It is possible to use multiple INCLUDEIF tags to create a series of conditional gates. Multiple INCLUDEIFs behave as if the conditions are ANDed together (not ORed), i.e. the more INCLUDEIFs used, the more restricted the report. This tag only works in the row section i.e. between the [LL_WEBREPORT_STARTROW /] and [LL_WEBREPORT_ENDROW /] tags.

Notes:

(See additional notes for the LL_WEBREPORT_EXITIF tag or Advanced Notes on Logical Expressions for more detail)

See the section on Advanced Notes on Logical Expressions for a list of Operators.
This tag affects the number of rows that are actually returned and displayed. For this reason, this tag has an impact on the ROWNUM tag which should not be used as part of the conditional logic for LL_WEBREPORT_INCLUDEIF.
This tag does not change the LL_REPTAG_TOTALROWS tag which will always reflect the number of rows that were actually available from the database table. To access the number of rows which are actually returned (i.e. that pass the conditional test), the LL_REPTAG_ACTUALROWS tag should be used. See the specific syntax information for these tags.
Expression Examples:

[LL_WEBREPORT_INCLUDEIF "[LL_REPTAG_&var1 /]" != "[LL_REPTAG=DATAID /]" /]
[LL_WEBREPORT_INCLUDEIF "Admin" == "[LL_REPTAG_USERNAME /]" /]
[LL_WEBREPORT_INCLUDEIF "1234" NOTIN "[LL_REPTAG_1 /]" /]
[LL_WEBREPORT_INCLUDEIF "*DELETED*" IN "[LL_REPTAG=keyfield /]" /]
[LL_WEBREPORT_INCLUDEIF "[LL_REPTAG_1 LENGTH /]" >= "10" AND "[LL_REPTAG=dataid /]" CHILDOF "[LL_REPTAG_&rootid /]" /]
[LL_WEBREPORT_INCLUDEIF "Case-sensitive name comparison" == "[LL_REPTAG=Name /]":USECASE OR "Case-insensitive name comparison" == "[LL_REPTAG=Name /]" /]
Take care that when using quotes not to nest the same style of quote within a tag.

For example, [LL_WEBREPORT_INCLUDEIF "[LL_REPTAG_"123456" /]" != "[LL_REPTAG=DATAID /]" /] is invalid syntax, because "123456" uses double-quotes, but is contained within a larger tag that is also surrounded by double-quotes - "[LL_REPTAG_"123456" /]".

In this scenario, use a mixture of single and double quotes. The following are both valid syntax:

[LL_WEBREPORT_INCLUDEIF "[LL_REPTAG_'123456' /]" /]
[LL_WEBREPORT_INCLUDEIF '[LL_REPTAG_"123456" /]' /]

		
[LL_WEBREPORT_INCLUDERANGE STARTROW:n ENDROW:n MAXROWS:n /]
Used to limit the rows returned by the WebReport to a range according to specified parameters.

At least one of the optional parameters: STARTROW, ENDROW or MAXROWS must be specified. These are treated as follows:

If only STARTROW is specified (no MAXROWS or ENDROW parameters are included) then ENDROW is assumed to be the last row of the data set
If no STARTROW is specified then the first row in the data set is assumed as the starting point
If MAXROWS and ENDROW are both specified then the more restrictive of these two parameters is used. E.g. if STARTROW=1, ENDROW=10 and MAXROWS=5 only 5 rows would be returned rather than 10
If the STARTROW is less than 1 then 1 is assumed
If the STARTROW is greater than the total number of rows in the data set then no rows will be returned
If the ENDROW is less than the STARTROW then no rows will be returned
The range of rows being returned are calculated after the other row filters (INCLUDEIF, EXITIF) have been evaluated. For example, given the following data set:

Source Row #	Data
1	Apple
2	Orange
3	Pear
4	Banana
5	Strawberry
6	Mango
If the row section had an LL_WEBREPORT_INCLUDEIF filter such as:

[LL_WEBREPORT_INCLUDEIF "[LL_REPTAG_SOURCEROWNUM ODDEVEN /]" == "EVEN" /]
This would result in only even row numbers being returned. E.g.:

Source Row #	Data
2	Orange
4	Banana
6	Mango
If an LL_WEBREPORT_INCLUDERANGE filter was also used, then this set of rows is whittled down further. E.g.:

[LL_WEBREPORT_INCLUDERANGE STARTROW:2 MAXROWS:2 /]
This would result in only 2 rows being returned, starting with row 2 from the data set returned after any LL_WEBREPORT_INCLUDEIF or LL_WEBREPORT_EXITIF tags have been processed. Using the previous table examples, this set would be:

Source Row #	Data
4	Banana
6	Mango
		
[LL_WEBREPORT_INSERTJSARRAY ARRAYNAME:<Optional Array Name> MULTIVALUE:<Column Name> /]
Used to automatically insert a JavaScript array with all of the report data arranged in a multi-dimensional array.

This will normally create an array called repData which is indexed numerically by row and column. It also creates a set of constants to allow the columns to be referenced. E.g. to reference the dataid column for a row of data the following could be used: document.write(repData[row][DATAID]);.

It is also possible to use an alternative array name using the ARRAYNAME: parameter. The MULTIVALUE: parameter can be used when one single column of a table is unique and the other columns are repeated.

For additional information about using this tag see: Automatically inserting JavaScript arrays.

		
[LL_WEBREPORT_INSERTJSON <multiple directives> /]
Used to automatically insert Content Server data into the output formatted as a JSON structure.

This tag supports a variety of "directives" that specify options regarding what data and formats to use. The available directives are:

@BROWSECOLUMNS, @ALLDATASOURCE, @ALLSTATIC, @ROWCOLUMNS, @FIELDS, @ADDJSVAR, @ESCAPETEXT, @EXCLUSIVE, @NODESTABLEFIELDS, @FILTEREDCOUNT, @TABLEREPORT
For additional information about these directives see: WebReports JSON formatted data.

		
