[LL_WEBREPORT_RESTCLIENT <multiple directives> /]
Used to send requests to external Rest APIs. Using this tag to make Rest requests to the current Content Server system isn't supported.

This tag supports a variety of directives to specify which parameters to use. The available directives are:

Directive	Description	Mandatory
@HOST	The name of the server, for example @HOST:'jsonplaceholder.typicode.com'.	Yes
@PORT	The port to connect to the server, for example @PORT:80.
The value must be a valid positive integer.	Yes
@URI	The Uniform Resource Identifier (URI), for example @URI:'/main/cs.exe/api/v1/nodes'.	Yes
@METHOD	The RestClient function to call, for example @METHOD:GET.

Supported methods are:

DELETE	Sends an HTTP delete.
GET	Sends an HTTP get.
PATCH	Sends an HTTP patch.
POST	Sends an HTTP post.
POSTDOC	Sends an HTTP post with the binary content of a Content Server document to upload with the request.
PUT	Sends an HTTP put.
PUTDOC	Sends an HTTP put with the binary content of a Content Server document to upload with the request.
Yes
@TIMEOUT	The request timeout (in seconds), for example @TIMEOUT:15.
The value must be a valid positive integer, and will default to 200 if not supplied.	No
@SECURE	Boolean. @SECURE:TRUE indicates to use HTTPS, otherwise HTTP will be used by default.	No
@CERTPATH	The path to default certificates.
If no certificate file (@CERTFILE) or keyfile (@KEYFILE) is supplied, this directory will be searched for the apppropriate certificate.
On Linux, this is usually /etc/ssl/certs.
On Windows, root certificates are loaded from the system store.
Pass an empty string to enable server verification with the system store.
If not specified, server verification will be disabled.

Requires that HTTPS is being used (@SECURE:TRUE).	No
@CERTFILE	The path/name of a user-supplied certificates file.
This file must contain a complete certificate chain.
Use if there is no default certificates store, or if the certificate is self-signed.

Requires that HTTPS is being used (@SECURE:TRUE), and that the @CERTPATH argument is populated.	No
@KEYFILE	The path/name of a user-supplied private key file, used for self-generated keys.

Requires that HTTPS is being used (@SECURE:TRUE), and that the @CERTPATH and @CERTFILE arguments are populated.	No
@PROXYHOST	The name of the proxy server, for example @PROXYHOST:'jsonplaceholder.typicode.com'.	No
@PROXYPORT	The port to connect to the proxy server, for example @PROXYPORT:8888.
The value must be a valid positive integer.	No
@PROXYUSERNAME	The username to connect to the proxy server.
The value should be stored in a secure constant, or entered as a prompted parameter, rather than be stored in text within the WebReport.	No
@PROXYPASSWORD	The password to connect to the proxy server.
The value should be stored in a secure constant, or entered as a prompted parameter, rather than be stored in text within the WebReport.	No
@HEADER	Assoc of key/value pairs to add to the header of the RestClient call.	No
@URLPARAMS	Assoc of key/value pairs to add to the URL query string. These will be URL-encoded if required.	No
@RESPONSE:<variable name>	Will return the response in an Assoc structure. The variable name is required.
The response Assoc will include common elements of the response, such as 'content', 'contentlength', 'contenttype', 'responseHeaders' and 'status'.
The data can be accessed using LL_REPTAG_! and the ASSOC sub-tag, for example [LL_REPTAG_!response ASSOC:status /].	No
@OUTPUT	The format of the output of the RestClient call. Will default to JSON if not supplied.

Supported arguments are:

JSON[:<variable name>]	Will return the output in a JSON structure. Optionally add a variable name to assign the returned JSON to a JavaScript variable.

For example, @OUTPUT:JSON:temp will add the following to the beginning of the JSON data:

var temp = <json data object>
ASSOC:<variable name>	Will return the output in an Assoc structure. The variable name is required.

For example, @OUTPUT:ASSOC:outputAssoc will assign the output to a variable called 'outputAssoc', and the data can be accessed using LL_REPTAG_!outputAssoc and the ASSOC sub-tag.

The output can be used with DSREQUESTDATA to set the data source of a sub-WebReport, for example:

[LL_REPTAG_$SWR RUNSWR:DSREQUESTDATA:[LL_REPTAG_!outputAssoc /]:DSFILETYPE:OSCRIPT /]
