CATACTION:<options>
This sub-tag provides capabilities to modify category and attribute metadata. With this tag you can:

add or remove a category from a node; and
add, set, or remove the value of a specific category attribute.
The <category> parameter accepts the data ID or name of the category.
The <attribute> parameter accepts the attribute ID or name of the attribute.
The <set> parameter accepts the attribute ID or name of the set.
[:Index] and [:Set Index] are optional parameters to target a specific attribute in a multi-valued attribute and multi-valued set. These values default to 1 if not set. You must give a value of [:Index] when using the [:Set Index] parameter.

The following table describes the syntax for the various usages of CATACTION. Each use case expects the DataID of the target node on which CATACTION will work. The parts in angle brackets are required; the parts in square brackets are optional.


Operation	Syntax	Description
Setting Attribute Values	CATACTION:SETVALUE:<category>:<attribute>[:Index][:Set Index]:<value>

SETVALUE supports two additional parameters when setting Table Key Lookup (TKL) attributes from the Attribute Extensions module: CASCADETKLS and RETURNCHANGES.

:CASCADETKLS will cascade the new value changes to dependent TKL attributes in the same category. This can be used with the NOCOMMIT attribute to set multiple attributes at once.

:RETURNCHANGES will return a RecArray containing a Record for each linked TKL attribute that has been updated with a cascaded value. This option can only be used directly after the CASCADETKLS parameter.

Note: Due to limitations in the underlying API, Table Key Lookup attributes within Category Sets are not supported in CATACTION.	Sets the attribute value at a given attribute and set index. To add a new row to a multi-value set, specify the 'ADDSETROW' keyword for the [:Set Index] parameter. Once added the new row can be targeted using the 'NEWROW' keyword for [:Set Index]. See example below.
CATACTION:ADDVALUE:<category>:<attribute>[:Index][:Set Index]:<value>	Appends a value to the end of multi-valued attribute. This tag ignores the [:Index] parameter.
CATACTION:INSERTVALUE:<category>:<attribute>[:Index][:Set Index]:<value>	Inserts a value at the given attribute index. This causes the existing attribute at that index and all subsequent attributes to shift down.
Optionally append :NOCOMMIT to SETVALUE, ADDVALUE and INSERTVALUE statements to delay the category update from being committed. This option is particularly useful if there are multiple CATACTION statements updating several attributes within a category. Omit NOCOMMIT from the final CATACTION statement for the category in order to commit the update.

Example:

[LL_REPTAG_MYID CATACTION:SETVALUE:"Cat 2 Mandatory Attributes":"Attr01":"a":NOCOMMIT /]
[LL_REPTAG_MYID CATACTION:SETVALUE:"Cat 2 Mandatory Attributes":"Attr02":"b" /]

will update a category containing two mandatory attributes. The first line will set the value of the Attr01 attribute but not commit it. The second line will set the value of the Attr02 attribute and then commit both changes at once.
Removing Attribute Values	CATACTION:REMOVEVALUE:<category>:<attribute>[:Index][:Set Index]	Removes the attribute at a given index. This causes the number of values in a multi-valued attribute to be reduced by one. If the attribute has only one value then the tag will have no effect.

Use ALL as the index value to remove all of the attribute values. The first value will be cleared rather than removed.
CATACTION:REMOVEVALUE:<category>:<set>[:Set Index]	Removes the row at the given set index from the given attribute set. This causes the number of rows in the attribute set to be reduced by one. If the attribute set contains only one row then the tag will have no effect.
CATACTION:CLEARVALUE:<category>:<attribute>[:Index][:Set Index]	Sets the attribute value at a given index to null. This does not change the number of values in a multi-valued attribute.
Optionally append :NOCOMMIT to REMOVEVALUE and CLEARVALUE statements to delay the category update from being committed. This option is particularly useful if there are multiple CATACTION statements updating several attributes within a category. Omit NOCOMMIT from the final CATACTION statement for the category in order to commit the update.

Example:

[LL_REPTAG_MYID CATACTION:CLEARVALUE:"MyCategory":"Attr01":NOCOMMIT /]
[LL_REPTAG_MYID CATACTION:CLEARVALUE:"MyCategory":"Attr02" /]

will clear the values in two attributes in a category. The first line will clear the value of the Attr01 attribute but not commit the change. The second line will clear the value of the Attr02 attribute and then commit both changes at once.
Adding/Removing Categories	CATACTION:ADD:<category>	Adds the given category to the node.
CATACTION:REMOVE:<category>	Removes the given category from the node.
CATACTION:UPGRADE:<category>	Upgrade the category to the latest version.
Copying category data	CATACTION:COPY:<target node ID>[:category]	Copies category data from the node in the main tag to the target node.
If the optional [:category] argument is not supplied then the target node's original category data will be deleted and replaced with the category data from the source node.
If the [:category] argument is supplied then only the category data for that category will be copied.
If the category already exists in the target node then the data will be overwritten.
Examples:

[LL_REPTAG_MYID CATACTION:COPY:12345 /] will replace the category data in node ID 12345 with the category data from the node in the main tag.

[LL_REPTAG_MYID CATACTION:COPY:12345:"Category 1" /] will copy the category data for "Category 1" from the node in the main tag to node ID 12345.
If "Category 1" already exists in the target node then it will be replaced with the data from the source node.
CATACTION:MERGE:<target node ID>:<USESOURCE or USETARGET>[:category]	Merges the category data from the source node into the target node.
If a category exists in both nodes then use the USESOURCE argument to use the data from the source node to overwrite the data in the target node, otherwise use the USETARGET argument to prevent the data in the target node from being overwritten.
If the [:category] argument is supplied then only the category data for that category will be copied.
Examples:

[LL_REPTAG_MYID CATACTION:MERGE:12345:USESOURCE /] will merge the category data from the node in the main tag to node ID 12345.
If a category exists in both the source and target nodes, the data from the source node will be used to overwrite the data in the target node.

[LL_REPTAG_MYID CATACTION:MERGE:12345:USETARGET /] will merge the category data from the node in the main tag to node ID 12345.
If a category exists in both the source and target nodes, the data in the target node for that category will not be overwritten.

[LL_REPTAG_MYID CATACTION:MERGE:12345:USESOURCE:"Category 1" /] will copy the category data for "Category 1" from the node in the main tag to node ID 12345.
If "Category 1" already exists in the target node then it will be replaced with the data from the source node.

[LL_REPTAG_MYID CATACTION:MERGE:12345:USETARGET:"Category 1" /] will copy the category data for "Category 1" from the node in the main tag to node ID 12345.
If "Category 1" already exists in the target node then it will not be overwritten.
Setting Category Inheritance	CATACTION:INHERITANCE:<category>:<value>	Sets category inheritance for a node. Valid values are "Enabled" or "Disabled".
Getting Attribute Data	CATACTION:GETVALUE:<category>:<attribute>[:Index][:Set Index]	Displays the value of the attribute.
CATACTION:SERIALIZE:<category>:<attribute>[:Index][:Set Index]	Returns a JSON representation of the attribute definition.
For example, consider the "Test Category" schema described here. Use the following syntax to set the "Trial Name" attribute on the Enterprise Workspace to "first":

[LL_REPTAG_"2000" CATACTION:SETVALUE:"Test Category":"TrialName":"first" /]
You can use the TODATE sub-tag to format a date string to set the value of a date attribute. For example, the following syntax will set the value of the 'Start Date' attribute to 24th April 1988:

[LL_REPTAG_"2000" CATACTION:SETVALUE:"Test Category":"Start Date":[LL_REPTAG_'24/04/1988' TODATE:'%d/%m/%Y' /] /]
To remove the "Test Category" from the Enterprise Workspace:

[LL_REPTAG_"2000" CATACTION:REMOVE:"Test Category" /]
Consider the "Type Testing Category" schema described here. Use the following syntax to add another row to the "Tester Details" set and to populate its fields. The 'ADDSETROW' keyword is only applicable to SETVALUE however the 'NEWROW' keyword can be used with SETVALUE, ADDVALUE, INSERTVALUE, REMOVEVALUE, and CLEARVALUE. In this example we are adding a new row of contact details to the "Tester Details" set.

[// Add a new row to the set using 'ADDSETROW'
[LL_REPTAG_"2000" CATACTION:SETVALUE:"Type Testing Category":"First Name":1:ADDSETROW:"Tom" /]

[// Target the new row added using the 'NEWROW' keyword
[LL_REPTAG_"2000" CATACTION:SETVALUE:"Type Testing Category":"Last Name":1:NEWROW:"Brady" /]
[LL_REPTAG_"2000" CATACTION:SETVALUE:"Type Testing Category":"Phone Number":1:NEWROW:"4168858129" /]
[LL_REPTAG_"2000" CATACTION:SETVALUE:"Type Testing Category":"Associates":1:NEWROW:"Jordan Gladstone" /]

[// Append values to the multi-valued 'Associates' attribute
[LL_REPTAG_"2000" CATACTION:ADDVALUE:"Type Testing Category":"Associates":2:NEWROW:"Chris Meyer" /]
[LL_REPTAG_"2000" CATACTION:ADDVALUE:"Type Testing Category":"Associates":3:NEWROW:"John Doe" /]
See also: TODATE   

		
