DATEDEC:<value>:<units>
Decrements the date returned by the main tag by the value and units specified.
Valid date formats for the main tag include [LL_REPTAG_DATETIME /], [LL_REPTAG_DATE /], and Content Server-formatted dates such as 'Sat Apr 16 00:00:00 2011', 'Feb 20 2010' and 'D/2012/12/25:00:00:00'.
The <value> parameter should be a positive integer.
The <units> parameter will be one of the following:

Units	Description
DAYS	This option will decrement the date by 'x' number of days.
WEEKS	This option will decrement the date by 'x' number of weeks.
SECONDS	This option will decrement the date by 'x' number of seconds.
Examples:

[// Here DATETIME and DATE tags return Mon Apr 11 00:00:00 2011
[LL_REPTAG_DATETIME DATEDEC:2:DAYS /]          [// Returns Sat Apr 09 00:00:00 2011
[LL_REPTAG_DATE DATEDEC:2:WEEKS /]          [// Returns Mon Mar 28 00:00:00 2011

[LL_REPTAG_'Sat Apr 16 10:23:32 2011' DATEDEC:86400:SECONDS /]          [// Returns Fri Apr 15 10:23:32 2011
[LL_REPTAG_'D/2012/12/25:00:00:00' DATEDEC:4:WEEKS /]          [// Tue Nov 27 00:00:00 2012

[// Here dueDate is a column from the data source and returns the date: Tue May 24 00:00:00 2011
[LL_REPTAG=dueDate DATEDEC:6:DAYS /]          [// Returns Wed May 18 00:00:00 2011
An empty string is returned if the main tag is empty. An error message will be returned if the main tag is not a valid date.

See also: DATE   DATEDIFF   DATEINC   DATEINTEGER   TODATE   TIMESINCE   

		
DATEDIFF:<reference date>:<units>
Returns the difference between the date in the main tag and the reference date (reference date - main tag date). If the reference date is omitted then the server's current date and time are used. An optional units parameter will convert the seconds to minutes, hours, days, etc. If no <units> parameter is provided, the difference will be returned in days by default. If the measured difference cannot be specified in a round number using the specified unit then a 2 digit decimal value is returned. For example, if the difference between two dates is 75 minutes and the parameter "HOURS" has been specified, then the value 1.25 would be returned.

Valid date formats for the main tag include [LL_REPTAG_DATETIME /], [LL_REPTAG_DATE /], and Content Server formatted dates (Eg. 'Sat Apr 16 00:00:00 2011', 'Feb 20 2010', 'D/2012/12/25:00:00:00').

The <reference date> parameter should also be a valid Content Server formatted date.

The <units> parameter can be one of the following: SECONDS, MINUTES, HOURS, DAYS, WEEKDAYS, WEEKS, MONTHS, YEARS, WEEKDAYS. The WEEKDAYS unit returns days but only non-weekend days. Thus if DAYS normally returns 10 but spans two weekends, WEEKDAYS would only return 6. If the lower date starts on a non-weekday, the calculation starts from the following Monday. If the higher date ends on a non-weekday, then the calculation ends on the preceding Friday.

Examples:

Tag	Result
[LL_REPTAG_"D/2010/5/30:0:0:0" DATEDIFF:"D/2011/5/30:0:0:0":DAYS /]	365
 [LL_REPTAG=modifyDate DATEDIFF:HOURS /]	Number of hours between the modified date (as returned from the DB) and todays date
 [LL_REPTAG=modifyDate DATEDIFF:"[LL_REPTAG_&dateparm /]":DAYS /]	The number of days between the modified date and a passed date parm
		
DATEINC:<value>:<units>
Increments the date returned by the main tag by the value and units specified. Valid date formats for the main tag include [LL_REPTAG_DATETIME /], [LL_REPTAG_DATE /], and Content Server formatted dates (Eg. 'Sat Apr 16 00:00:00 2011', 'Feb 20 2010', 'D/2012/12/25:00:00:00'). The <value> parameter should be an integer, greater than zero. The <units> parameter will be one of the following:

Units	Description
DAYS	This option will increment the date by 'x' number of days.
WEEKS	This option will increment the date by 'x' number of weeks.
SECONDS	This option will increment the date by 'x' number of seconds.
WEEKDAYS	This option will increment the date by 'x' number of days, excluding weekends.
Examples:

[// Here DATETIME and DATE tags return Mon Apr 11 00:00:00 2011
[LL_REPTAG_DATETIME DATEINC:2:DAYS /]          [// Returns Wed Apr 13 00:00:00 2011
[LL_REPTAG_DATE DATEINC:2:WEEKS /]          [// Returns Mon Apr 25 00:00:00 2011

[LL_REPTAG_'Sat Apr 16 10:23:32 2011' DATEINC:86400:SECONDS /]          [// Returns Sun Apr 17 10:23:32 2011
[LL_REPTAG_'Feb 20 2010' DATEINC:10:WEEKDAYS /]          [// Returns Fri Mar 05 00:00:00 2010
[LL_REPTAG_'D/2012/12/25:00:00:00' DATEINC:4:WEEKS /]          [// Tue Jan 22 00:00:00 2011

[// Here dueDate is a column from the data source and returns the date: Tue May 24 00:00:00 2011
[LL_REPTAG=dueDate DATEINC:60:DAYS /]          [// Returns Sat Jul 23 00:00:00 2011
An empty string is returned if the main tag is empty. An error message will be returned if the main tag is not a valid date.

See also: DATE   DATEDEC   DATEDIFF   DATEINTEGER   TODATE   TIMESINCE   

		
