ESCAPEFORJS:<mode>
Converts a string using the same encoding as the specified JavaScript escape function:

Escape Mode	Description
ESCAPEFORJS:ESCAPE	Uses the JavaScript escape() function, which does not encode: @/+
ESCAPEFORJS:ENCODEURI	Uses the JavaScript encodeURI() function, which does not encode: ~!@#$&()=:/,;?+'
ESCAPEFORJS:ENCODEURICOMPONENT	Uses the JavaScript encodeURIComponent(), which does not encode: ~!*()'
ESCAPEFORJS:HEX
or
ESCAPEFORJS:HEX:<quoteChar>	
Returns a hex-escaped string for use in Javascript, which is useful in preventing Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) vulnerabilities. The returned string is wrapped with the <quoteChar> and any instances of the <quoteChar> within the string itself will be escaped. If the <quoteChar> parameter is not passed, the ' (single quote) character is used by default. Space characters become \x20, tab characters \x09, and back slashes \x5c. For example:

[LL_REPTAG_"joe's tools\utils" ESCAPEFORJS:HEX /]
resolves to: 'joe\x27s\x20tools\x5cutils' (including the single quote characters)
The optional <quoteChar> parameter can be used used to delimit the string, for example:

[LL_REPTAG_'joe said "hello"' ESCAPEFORJS:HEX:'"' /]
resolves to: "joe\x20said\x20\x22hello\x22" (including the double quote characters)
This can be used to prevent XSS vulnerabilities within a WebReport, for example:

var theURL = "[LL_REPTAG_&myURLParm /]";
This syntax is vulnerable to an XSS attack, as the value of the 'myURLParm' parameter in the request will replace the [LL_REPTAG_&myURLParm /] tag. The above syntax allows an attacker to terminate the variable string early and append additional Javascript that will be executed by the browser. A simple value that demonstrates injecting a simple Javascript alert statement is this:

&theURL=%27"%3Balert(%27XSS%27)//
The generated output would be:

var theURL = "'";alert('XSS')//";
You can prevent this type of injection by using this ESCAPEFORJS:HEX sub-tag, which will encode the value and wrap it in single quotes or another character provided in the <quoteChar> parameter. To prevent the XSS vulnerability, the syntax would look like this:

var theURL = [LL_REPTAG_&myURLParm ESCAPEFORJS:HEX /];
The generated output now would be:

var theURL = '\x27\x22\x3balert\x28\x27XSS\x27\x29\x2f\x2f';
While the value is still injected, it is not actually executed by the Javascript parser as it is contained within a string and can't be terminated early to add in other blocks of Javascript. The resulting string will be automatically decoded when parsed by a Javascript interpreter, but still handled as a string.

For example:

[LL_REPTAG_'"joe+B,smith"@example.com' ESCAPEFORJS:ENCODEURI /]
would resolve to: %22joe+B,smith%22@example%2Ecom

		
