ONERROR:<parm>
A sub-tag error typically occurs when a sub-tag receives invalid data or an invalid parameter. The ONERROR sub-tag allows the developer to change the default error message when an error occurs. The position of the ONERROR sub-tag in the list of sub-tags is irrelevant, and applies to every sub-tag in the list.

The following options describe the different ways ONERROR can be used:

Error Type	Description
ONERROR:BLANK[:BREAK]	This option will replace any standard error message with a blank string, which is useful for preventing error messages from being displayed.
ONERROR:SHORT[:BREAK]	This option will display a short version of the error message, which consists of the sub-tag in question and an error number.
ONERROR:LONG[:BREAK]	This option will display a full error message for the sub-tag in question.
ONERROR:CUSTOM:<error message>[:BREAK]	This option allows the developer to specify their own error message for a sub-tag.
ONERROR:SYSTEM:<Severity Level>[Custom error message][:BREAK]	This option will log a system fault to the System Fault Log.
The error message in the main tag will be used, unless it is overwritten with a custom error message.
ONERROR:BUSINESS:<Severity Level>[Custom error message][:BREAK]	This option will log a business fault to the System Fault Log.
The error message in the main tag will be used, unless it is overwritten with a custom error message.
The optional BREAK parameter prevents subsequent sub-tags from being processed as soon as the first error occurs.

Valid Severity Levels for SYSTEM and BUSINESS error types are:

INFO
WARNING
ERROR
SEVERE
CRITICAL

Examples

[LL_REPTAG_"somestring" LIST:4 INC /]

The LIST:4 sub-tag produces an error because the data (i.e., "somestring") isn't a valid list. The INC sub-tag receives the error message from LIST, which is also invalid (i.e., not an integer), and therefore produces an error:
* INC: Invalid (non-integer) data value *
The error message can be customized in a number of ways as follows. Notice that the placement of ONERROR is irrelevant:
[LL_REPTAG_"somestring" LIST:4 ONERROR:SHORT INC /]
returns: * INC: 1002 *
[LL_REPTAG_"somestring" LIST:4 INC ONERROR:CUSTOM:"Custom Error Message" /]
returns: * INC: Custom Error Message *
[LL_REPTAG_"somestring" LIST:4 ONERROR:SYSTEM:WARNING /]

This tag will log a system fault in the System Fault Log with Severity = "Warning", Event Type = "WebReport System Fault" and Details = "Raised from WebReport ID: <WebReport ID>. * LIST: Data is not a valid list".
[LL_REPTAG_"somestring" LIST:4 ONERROR:BUSINESS:INFO:"An error has occurred." /]

This tag will log a business fault in the System Fault Log with Severity = "Info", Event Type = "WebReport Business Fault" and Details = "Raised from WebReport ID: <WebReport ID>. An error has occurred.".
Adding the BREAK parameter causes processing to stop as soon as the first error occurs. In the following example, the error occurs in the LIST sub-tag, and therefore the INC sub-tag isn't processed:

[LL_REPTAG_"somestring" LIST:4 INC ONERROR:LONG:BREAK /]
returns: * LIST: Data is not a valid list *
See also: LOGFAULT   

		
PARSECSV
This sub-tag parses a string with comma-separated values and returns a structured RecArray.

For example:

[LL_REPTAG_'A,B,C' PARSECSV /]
returns:

V{<'Column1','Column2','Column3'><'A','B','C'>}.
See also: LL_WEBREPORT_FOR   

		
PATCHANGE:<find pattern>:<new pattern>
or
PATCHANGE:<find patt.>:<new patt>:<ignoreCase?>
Returns a modified version of the main tag based on the find and replace patterns specified.

The find pattern is specified with a series of special operators as per the table below. This is a simplified and slightly modified subset of UNIX's regular expression pattern matching. For Content Server developers this syntax is based on the Oscript PATFIND and PATCHANGE builtins. This is almost identical to the PATFIND syntax but includes the ability to specify parts of the find pattern which can be referenced for substitution in the replace pattern. If no match if found, the original tag contents is returned unchanged.

The replace pattern can also include some special characters which are also shown below. The replace pattern is normally a fixed pattern of characters but any characters to be retained from the find pattern are enclosed in the <...> characters and then inserted in the replace pattern using the # symbol. By default this sub-tag ignores the case of characters when matching. Specifying FALSE as a third parameter causes the change operation to be case sensitive.

For more detailed information about PATFIND or PATCHANGE the Content Server SDK documentation should be consulted.

Find Pattern Special Characters

 c	 Match exact character (c is any character here)
 @c	 Match escaped character ( such as @%, @[, @*)
 ?	 Match any character except end of line
 %	 Match beginning of line
 $	 Match end of line (null string before end of line)
 [...]	 Match character class (any one of 'these' characters, such as [abc] or [a-z])
 [!...]	 Match negated character class (all but these characters, such as [! ] for no spaces)
 *	 Match zero or more occurrences of the previous element, such as [0-9]* for zero or more digits
 +	 Match one or more occurrences of the previous element, such as [A-Za-z]+ for one or more letters
 <...>	 Brackets tagged material which is specially extracted for later reference or use
Replace Pattern Special Characters

 &	 Ditto (Whole String)
 @c	 escaped character (such as @&)
 #n	 Tagged substring insertion
PATCHANGE Examples:

This example of the PATCHANGE sub-tag assumes that the associated tag contains the string:

This is a test sentence 123, end

PATCHANGE:"?* <t?+t> *sen[!0-9]+<[0-9]+>?*":"Word: #1; Number: #2" would return:

Word: test; Number: 123
In this example:

Any characters which are matched (but not enclosed in < >) will not be included in the replacement.
<t?+t> finds a match with the word "test". Because it is the first "tagged substring", this word is substituted in place of #1 in the replace string.
<[0-9]+> finds a match with the numbers "123". Because it is the second "tagged substring", these characters are substituted in place of #2 in the replace string.
The part of the find pattern: sen[!0-9]+ finds the characters "sen" followed by 1 or more characters which are NOT numbers.
		
PATFIND:<find pattern>
or
PATFIND:<find pattern>:<ignoreCase?>
Returns either TRUE or FALSE depending on whether the specified pattern is found within the string returned by the main tag. The find pattern is specified with a series of special operators as per the table below. This is a simplified and slightly modified subset of UNIX's regular expression pattern matching. For Content Server developers this syntax is based on the Oscript PATFIND and PATCHANGE builtins. By default this sub-tag ignores the case of characters when matching. Specifying FALSE as a second parameter causes the find operation to be case sensitive. For more information about PATFIND or PATCHANGE the Content Server SDK documentation should be consulted.

 c	 Match exact character (c is any character here)
 @c	 Match escaped character ( such as @%, @[, @*)
 ?	 Match any character except end of line
 %	 Match beginning of line
 $	 Match end of line (null string before end of line)
 [...]	 Match character class (any one of 'these' characters, such as [abc] or [a-z])
 [!...]	 Match negated character class (all but these characters, such as [! ] for no spaces)
 *	 Match zero or more occurrences of the previous element, such as [0-9]* for zero or more digits
 +	 Match one or more occurrences of the previous element, such as [A-Za-z]+ for one or more letters
PATFIND Examples:

This example of the PATFIND sub-tag assumes that the associated tag contains the string:

This is a test sentence 123, end

PATFIND:"sen?+ *[0-9]+" would return TRUE

This pattern specifies the specific characters: sen followed by 1 or more characters: ?+; 0 or more spaces: <sp>*; and 1 or more digits: [0-9]*. This would match on the string: "sentence 123" and therefore the tag returns true.

		
PERMACTION:<operation>
This sub-tag provides the flexibility to add, remove and modify permissions of content within Content Server. Due to the powerful nature of this sub-tag, its effects should be carefully understood before usage. The sub-tag behaves like the other WebReports sub-tags in that you cannot modify the permissions of nodes that you do not have permissions to do so via the regular interface. The key difference is that using WebReports allows these changes to be automated so they can be done much faster than through the interface.

Content Server supports three permission models: Standard permission model (Eg. Content Server objects such as documents, folders, etc), Project permission model (Eg. projects), and the Work Items permission model (Eg. discussions, channels, task lists, etc). The PERMACTION sub-tag provides the functionality to update all 3 permission models. The table below describes how to use the PERMACTION sub-tag and the object(s) it affects. We will use SPM (Standard Permission Model), PPM (Project Permission model) and WPM (Work Items Permission Model) to indicate the permission model and objects affected.

Action	Operation	Description
ACL:<userID>	PERMACTION:ACL:<userID>:REMOVE	Removes the user or group specified by <userID> from a Content Server object's permission ACL. This operation is supported by SPM and WPM objects.
PERMACTION:ACL:<userID>:UPDATE:<perms>	Updates the permissions specified by <perms> for the user or group specified by <userID> in a Content Server object's permission ACL. If the user or group specified is not currently in the ACL, they will be added. This operation is supported by SPM and WPM objects.
OWNER	PERMACTION:OWNER:UPDATE:<perms>	Updates the permissions specified by <perms> for the current owner in the Content Server object's default access. This operation is supported by SPM and WPM objects.
PERMACTION:OWNER:CHANGE:<userID>:<perms>	Sets the owner section of the default access for a Content Server object's permissions to the user specified by <userID> with the permissions specified by <perms>. This operation is supported by SPM and WPM objects.
PERMACTION:OWNER:REMOVE	Removes the current owner from the Default Access section of permissions for the Content Server object. This will set the OWNER section of Default Access to "No Owner". This operation is supported by SPM and WPM objects.
OWNERGROUP	PERMACTION:OWNERGROUP:UPDATE:<perms>	Updates the permissions specified by <perms> for the current owner group in the Content Server object's default access. This operation is supported by SPM and WPM objects.
PERMACTION:OWNERGROUP:CHANGE:<userID>:<perms>	Sets the owner group section of the default access for a Content Server object's permissions to the group specified by <userID> with the permissions specified by <perms>. This operation is supported by SPM and WPM objects.
PERMACTION:OWNERGROUP:REMOVE	Removes the current owner group from the default access section of permissions for the Content Server object. This will set the owner group section of Default Access to "No Owner Group". This operation is supported by SPM and WPM objects.
PUBLIC	PERMACTION:PUBLIC:UPDATE:<perms>	Updates the permissions specified by <perms> for public access in the Content Server object's default access. This operation is supported by SPM, PPM, and WPM objects.
PERMACTION:PUBLIC:REMOVE	Removes public access from the default access section of permissions for the Content Server object. This will set the public access section of Default Access to "No Public Access". This operation is supported by SPM and WPM objects.
<role>
(Projects only)	PERMACTION:<role>:UPDATE:<userID>	Updates the Role specified by <role> for the user or group specified by <userID> in the Project's Participant page. If the user or group specified is not a Project Participant, they will be added. This operation is only supported by PPM objects.
PERMACTION:<role>:REMOVE:<userID>	Removes the user or group specified by <userID> from the Role specified by <role> in the Project's Participant page. This operation is only supported by PPM objects.
PERMACTION:<role>:REMOVE	Removes all users and groups with the specified <role> from the Project's Participant page. This operation is only supported by PPM objects.
This sub-tag expects the data id of the content in Content Server the user wants to perform permission actions upon, to be specified in the main tag. For SPM objects (Eg. documents, folders, etc), there are two ways to specify permissions for any action that requires <perms>; either a decimal number representing a binary bit mask for Content Server permissions, which some developers may be familiar with (and unfortunately is too much to display here), or instead the user can specify a list of permissions using any combination of the following keywords:

Keyword	Permission Affected
SEE	See
SEECONTENTS	See Contents
MODIFY	Modify
EDITATTRS	Edit Attributes
ADDITEMS	Add Items
RESERVE	Reserve or Checkout
ADDMAJORVERSION	Add Major Version
DELETEVERS	Delete Versions
DELETE	Delete the Object
EDITPERMS	Edit Permissions
Note that the permissions specified in this sub-tag follow the permissions model of the Content Server interface, meaning that selecting just one permission will also set the other required permissions, eg. choosing "MODIFY" will set the "See", "See Contents" and "Modify" permisisons for an object.

To specify permissions for WPM objects (Eg. discussions, channels, task lists, etc), the following table displays the keywords that can be substituted for <perms> in any of the applicable PERMACTION operations:

Keyword
NONE
READ
WRITE
ADMINISTER
To specify permissions for PPM objects (Eg. Projects), the following table displays the 3 types of roles that can be substituted for <role> in the applicable PERMACTION operations:

Keyword
COORD
MEMBER
GUEST
Where COORD indicates a Coordinator. For the scenario where PUBLIC permissions can be updated for PPM objects (PERMACTION:PUBLIC:UPDATE:<perms>), the acceptable values for <perms> in this case is ENABLED or DISABLED.

PERMACTION Examples:

If a user creating a WebReport wants to update the permissions for a user with a user ID of 1234 in the ACL of a document (in this case DATAID), with the permissions of See and See Contents, they could use either:

[LL_REPTAG=DATAID PERMACTION:ACL:1234:UPDATE:"SEE,SEECONTENTS" /] which is using the list of keywords to specify the permissions to update,
or
[LL_REPTAG=DATAID PERMACTION:ACL:1234:UPDATE:36995 /] which is specifying a decimal representation of the binary bit mask for See and See Contents.
If a user creating a WebReport wants to change the Owner of a task list to the Admin user (1000) and give them Administer access, they can use the following tag:

[LL_REPTAG=DATAID PERMACTION:OWNER:CHANGE:1000:ADMINISTER /] where DATAID returns the dataID of the task list and 'ADMINISTER' is a keyword for WPM objects.
If a user creating a WebReport wants to set the Admin user (1000) in a Project to a Member role, the following tag can be used:

[LL_REPTAG=DATAID PERMACTION:MEMBER:UPDATE:1000 /] where DATAID returns the dataID of the project and 'MEMBER' is a keyword for PPM objects.
		
PERMCHECK:<parm>
or
PERMCHECK:<parm>:<user/group ID>
Checks if the current (or a specified) user has permission to perform the specified action for that object. Either TRUE or FALSE is returned depending on the result of this verification.

PERMCHECK Additional Notes:

When this tag is used, the value that would normally be returned by the main tag is replaced by either TRUE or FALSE.
This tag is only valid when used with a tag that normally returns a valid Content Server object id. For example, IDs, DATAIDs and VOLUMEIDs. An invalid report tag will cause this sub-tag to return false.
The specified actions (see, edit, delete) map to Content Server permissions as shown in the chart below. To use this chart, find the highest level of Content Server permission that the user is expected to have to return true from this tag. Then use the setting listed under Permcheck Action.
Permcheck Action	Forms	DTree Objects
NONE
SEE	SEE
SEECONTENTS	SEE	SEE CONTENTS
EDIT	EDIT STATIONERY	MODIFY
EDIT	SQL SUBMIT	EDIT ATTRIBUTES
EDIT		DELETE VERSIONS
EDIT	RESERVE
EDIT	ADD ITEMS
MODIFY	MODIFY
EDITATTRIBUTES	EDIT ATTRIBUTES
ADDITEMS	ADD ITEMS
RESERVE	RESERVE
ADDMAJORVERSION	ADD MAJOR VERSION
DELETE	ADMINISTER	DELETE
DELETEVERSIONS		DELETE VERSIONS
EDITPERMISSIONS	EDIT PERMISSIONS
PERMCHECK Examples:

If the EDIT action has been specified against a form dataid, then the tag will only return true if the user has at least Edit Stationery permission for the associated form.

To make sure that a delete button is only visible for users who have "Administer" permission to an associated form, the following WebReport declaration could be used (this assumes that form DataID is being returned in the underlying report data):

[LL_WEBREPORT_IF "[LL_REPTAG=DATAID PERMCHECK:DELETE /]" == "TRUE" /]
   <INPUT TYPE=BUTTON NAME="del" VALUE="Delete" ONCLICK="deleteItem()">
[LL_WEBREPORT_ENDIF /]
This could also be done using JavaScript code as below; however, this code will still be visible if a user views the source HTML from their browser.

if ( "[LL_REPTAG=DATAID PERMCHECK:DELETE /]" == "TRUE" ) {
   document.write('<INPUT TYPE=BUTTON NAME="delbutton" VALUE="Delete" ONCLICK="deleteItem();">');
};
		
PERMINFO:<format>
For a valid node ID, this sub-tag will a return a list of Assocs containing permission data for the node according to the format parameter that has been provided.

Can be chained with the LIST and ASSOC sub-tags to return more specific information.

Only returns data if the user has Edit Permissions on the node, otherwise an empty string will be returned.

Examples:

PERMINFO LIST:1 ASSOC:NAME will return the name of the node Owner.
PERMINFO:PUBLICACCESS LIST:1 ASSOC:PERMASSOC ASSOC:RESERVE will return true or false depending on whether Public Access has Reserve permission on the node.


Format	Description
PERMINFO	Returns a list containing separate Assocs for the Owner, Owner Group, Public Access and any Assigned Access entries.

The first Assoc will contain the permission data for the Owner.
The second Assoc will contain the permission data for the Owner Group.
The third Assoc will contain the permission data for Public Access.
If there are any Assigned Access entries then there will be a separate Assoc for each one from the fourth list entry onwards.
PERMINFO:OWNER	Returns a list containing an Assoc containing the permission data for the Owner.
PERMINFO:OWNERGROUP	Returns a list containing an Assoc containing the permission data for the Owner Group.
PERMINFO:PUBLICACCESS	Returns a list containing an Assoc containing the permission data for Public Access.
PERMINFO:ASSIGNEDACCESS	Returns a list containing separate Assocs for each entry in Assigned Access.
See also: ASSOC   LIST   

		
PERMTOASSOC
This sub-tag converts a permission bitmask into an Assoc for easier reading. For example:

[LL_REPTAG_'36995' PERMTOASSOC /],
returns:

A<1,?,'Create'=false,'Delete'=false,'DeleteVer'=false,'EditAttr'=false,'EditPerm'=false,'Modify'=false,'Reserve'=false,'See'=true,'SeeContent'=true>.
See also: ASSOC   PERMACTION   

		
PLUCK:<field>
The PLUCK sub-tag is used to extract a value from a collection of Records or Assocs, and returns the values as a List. The main tag must be a RecArray or List of Assocs or Records.

For example, the following tag will extract all the NAME values from the data source:

[LL_REPTAG_DATASOURCE PLUCK:NAME /]
returns:

{'Show All [Type] Items','My Tasks Due Next Week','All Tasks Due Next Week', ... }
See also: ASSOC   LIST   RECORD   

		
PLURALIZE:<suffix>
Returns a plural suffix if the main tag is not 1. By default, this suffix is 's'.

For example,

[LL_REPTAG_DATASOURCE LENGTH /] row[LL_REPTAG_DATASOURCE LENGTH PLURALIZE /]
If [LL_REPTAG_DATASOURCE LENGTH /] is 1, the output will be "1 row". If [LL_REPTAG_DATASOURCE LENGTH /] is 2, the output will be "2 rows".

		
POACTION:<operation>
Provides the ability to perform various actions from the Physical Objects module, like Assigning/Removing Transfer contents, and Circulating Physical Object items.

Action	Operation	Description
ASSIGNLOCATOR	POACTION:ASSIGNLOCATOR:<Facility>:<Area>:<LocatorName>
or
POACTION:ASSIGNLOCATOR:<Facility>:<Area>:<LocatorName>:<OffsiteStorageID>	Assigns Locators to the Physical Item node that was supplied in the data tag.

Expects a single NodeID in the data tag which must be a Physical Object node. This tag respects the core Physical Object behavior and will fail if:
The item does not already have a Locator Type assigned to it.
The selected Locator is managed and the item does not fit the conditions.
The Locator does not have enough space.
Example:
The following will assign a Locator named "Important Box" that's in the area named "Important Area" which is in the Facility named "Important Facility" to the Physical Object node that has a NodeID of 12345:

[LL_REPTAG_"12345" POACTION:ASSIGNLOCATOR:"Important Facility":"Important Area":"Important Box" /]

The optional OffsiteStorageID parameter can be used to set the Offsite Storage ID while assigning the Locator.
REMOVELOCATOR	POACTION:REMOVELOCATOR	Removes Physical Item node that was supplied in the data tag from Locator.

Expects a single NodeID in the data tag which must be a Physical Object node.

Example:
The following will remove the Physical Object node that has a NodeID of 12345 from locator:

[LL_REPTAG_"12345" POACTION:REMOVELOCATOR /]
ASSIGNBOX	POACTION:ASSIGNBOX:<NodeIDToAssignBox>	Assigns the Physical Item specified in the NodeIDToAssignBox parameter to a Box. The data tag should be an Assoc containing the following fields which can be used to set information when the item is assigned to a Box:
Field	Mandatory	Description
BoxID	required	The Box to which the content will be assigned.
UpdateStatus	optional	Update Status when assigning content to a Box. If this field isn't specified, false will be used.
UpdateLocation	optional	Update Location when assigning content to a Box. If this field isn't specified, false will be used.

Examples:

The following will assign physical item that has a NodeID of 12345 to a Box that has a NodeID of 54321:

[LL_REPTAG_'{{ "BoxID", 54321 }, { "UpdateStatus", TRUE }, { "UpdateLocation", TRUE }}' ASSOCACTION:CREATE SETVAR:myAssoc /]
[LL_REPTAG_%myAssoc CURRENTVAL POACTION:ASSIGNBOX:12345 /]
CIRCULATE	POACTION:CIRCULATE:BORROW:<IDToBorrow>	Borrows the node with a NodeID specified as the IDToBorrow parameter. The data tag should be an Assoc containing the following Borrow fields and values:
FieldName	Mandatory	Accepted Value
Location	optional	The current filing location.
UserID	required if ClientID is not specified	The UserID of the borrower.
The UserID or the ClientID needs to be specified or the action will fail.
ClientID	required if UserID is not specified	The ClientID of the external borrower.
The ClientID or the UserID needs to be specified or the action will fail.
SecurityOverride	optional	If the borrower is a Content Server user who does not have See Contents permissions, the object can only be charged to the user if SecurityOverride is set to True. If this field is not passed, the system default setting will be used.
BorrowDate	optional	If this field is not passed to the PhysObjChargeOut function, it will be set to the current date.
ReturnByDate	optional	If this field is not passed to the PhysObjChargeOut function, it will be set to the current date plus the number of days default setting in the Physical Objects module.
Comments	optional	The comments about a borrow.
ObtainedByID	optional	Information about the courier of borrowed items.
Pass	optional	If this field is not passed to the PhysObjChargeOut function, the item is charged out. If this field is passed and it equals TRUE, the item is passed to another borrower.
Acknowledge	optional	Flag that indicates if acknowledgement is required. Possible values: 1=Required, 2=Not Required. If this field is not passed, the system default setting will be used.

Examples:

The following will borrow a node with the NodeID of 12345, set the user who borrowed it to the Admin user (UserId of 1000), set the Borrow Date to the current date, and set the Return Date to the current date plus the default number of days specified in the Physical Objects System Settings:

[LL_REPTAG_{ { "UserID", 1000 } } ASSOCACTION:CREATE SETVAR:myAssoc /]
[LL_REPTAG_%myAssoc CURRENTVAL POACTION:CIRCULATE:BORROW:12345 /]

The following will borrow a node with the NodeID of 12345, set the user who borrowed it to the External Client with ClientID EC1, set the Borrow Date to the current date, and set the Return Date to the current date plus the default number of days specified in the Physical Objects System Settings:

[LL_REPTAG_{ { "ClientID", "EC1" } } ASSOCACTION:CREATE SETVAR:myAssoc /]
[LL_REPTAG_%myAssoc CURRENTVAL POACTION:CIRCULATE:BORROW:12345 /]

The fields listed above can be used to set additional borrow information if necessary. For example, the following will borrow a node with the nodeID of 12345 and set various bits of data using custom information and not the default settings:

[LL_REPTAG_{{ "UserID", 1000 }, {"Location","MAINWAREHOUSE"}, {"BorrowDate","[LL_REPTAG_DATE DATEDEC:5:DAYS /]"}, {"ReturnByDate","[LL_REPTAG_DATE DATEINC:2:WEEKS /]"}} ASSOCACTION:CREATE SETVAR:myAssoc /]
[LL_REPTAG_%myAssoc CURRENTVAL POACTION:CIRCULATE:BORROW:12345 /]
POACTION:CIRCULATE:RETURN:<NodeIDToReturn>	Returns the borrowed Physical Item specified in the NodeIDToReturn parameter. The data tag should be either blank or an Assoc containing the following fields which can be used to set optional information when the item is returned:
Field	Description
Comments	These comments are stored with audit data when item is returned.
Date	The Return Date for the item. If this field isn't specified, the current date will be used.
Location	Current Location of the Physical Item.
Home	If included in the Assoc, the Current Location of the Physical Item will be updated with the Home Location. This is an integer value, but the value itself is ignored.

Examples:

The following will return an item that has a NodeID of 12345, using the current date as the Return Date:

[LL_REPTAG_'' POACTION:CIRCULATE:RETURN:12345 /]

The above additional fields can be supplied in an Assoc in the data tag to set the optional values:

[LL_REPTAG_{ { "Comments", "These comments will be stored when the item is returned." }, {"Date","[LL_REPTAG_DATE /]"}, {"Location","MAINWAREHOUSE"}, {"Home",1} } ASSOCACTION:CREATE SETVAR:myAssoc /]
[LL_REPTAG_%myAssoc CURRENTVAL POACTION:CIRCULATE:RETURN:12345 /]
POACTION:CIRCULATE:CANCEL:<NodeIDToCancel>	Cancels the borrowed Physical Item specified in the NodeIDToCancel parameter. The data tag should be either blank or an Assoc containing fields which can be used to set optional information when the item is cancelled. The fields available are the same as the POACTION:CIRCULATE:RETURN subtag above.

Examples:

The following will cancel the borrow on an item that has a NodeID of 12345, using the current date as the Return Date:

[LL_REPTAG_'' POACTION:CIRCULATE:CANCEL:12345 /]

The above additional fields can be supplied in an Assoc in the data tag to set the optional values:

[LL_REPTAG_{ { "Comments", "These comments will be stored when the item is canceled." }, {"Date",[LL_REPTAG_DATE /]}, {"Location","MAINWAREHOUSE"}, {"Home",1} } ASSOCACTION:CREATE SETVAR:myAssoc /]
[LL_REPTAG_%myAssoc CURRENTVAL POACTION:CIRCULATE:CANCEL:12345 /]
TRANSFER	POACTION:TRANSFER:CREATE:<TransferID>:<CreateDate>	Creates a Transfer. The TransferID parameter will be the new Transfer's ID. The CreateDate parameter cannot be greater than the current date - only dates prior to the current date are allowed. If the CreateDate parameter is not provided, the current date will be used as the default.

Additional information can be set by passing an Assoc in the data tag containing the following optional data:

Field	Accepted Value
UserID	The UserID of the User responsible for the Transfer.
Comments	Additional comments associated with the Transfer.
EstSize	The estimated size of the Transfer. This can be the sum of the sizes of the boxes, or the total number of boxes in the transfer.
FromDate	The starting Date for the Transfer. This value should be a valid Content Server Date.
ToDate	The end Date for the Transfer. This value should be a valid Content Server Date.
TransferContent	A description for the content.

Examples:

The following will create a Transfer using the current date for the Create Date:
[LL_REPTAG_"" POACTION:TRANSFER:CREATE:"My Transfer":[LL_REPTAG_DATE /] /]

The following will create a Transfer and set additional information at the same time:

[// The CreateDate parameter in this example will be 5 days prior to the current date:
[LL_REPTAG_{{ "UserID", 1000 }, {"Comments", "This is a comment on the Transfer."}, {"EstSize", "20" }, {"FromDate", "[LL_REPTAG_DATE /]"}, {"ToDate", "[LL_REPTAG_DATE DATEINC:3:DAYS /]"}, {"TransferContent", "This is a comment on the Transfer contents."}} ASSOCACTION:CREATE SETVAR:transferInfo /]
[LL_REPTAG_%transferInfo CURRENTVAL POACTION:TRANSFER:CREATE:"My Transfer":[LL_REPTAG_DATE DATEDEC:5:DAYS /] /]
POACTION:TRANSFER:ASSIGN:<TransferID>
or
