SETEMAILATTACH
This sub-tag attaches documents to email destinations. The main tag or sub-tag to the left must contain the dataid of a Content Server document. This sub-tag is destination specific and will only function in combination with the email destination. It should be noted that each time this sub-tag is used a document is attached to the destination email so it would be easy to overload this delivery mechanism. It is recommended to use WebReports variables to keep a running total of the file sizes and so stop attaching documents when a given threshold is exceeded.

Example:

[LL_WEBREPORT_IF "[LL_REPTAG=DATAID NODEINFO:SIZE:BYTES ADDVAR:TOT CURRENTVAL /]" < "500000" /]
   [LL_REPTAG=DATAID SETEMAILATTACH /]
[LL_WEBREPORT_ENDIF /]
Here the DATAID column is being returned from the data source. NODEINFO:SIZE:BYTES takes the dataid and returns the size of the latest version of the node in bytes. ADDVAR takes the size in bytes for each row and adds the new value to the user-defined variable TOT. CURRENTVAL is then used to get the running total of the calculation (i.e. contents of TOT variable). A WebReport IF checks if the total size of all the nodes so far is less than 500,000 bytes (~0.5MB). If the total size is less than 0.5MB the document will be attached to the email.

		
SETFORM:<field details>
or
SETFORM:<field details>:NEXTROW
or
SETFORM:SEQ (update mode only)
or
SETFORM:NEXTSEQ (update mode only)
or
SETFORM:NEXTKEY:<column name> (update mode only)
This sub-tag stores the value of the data tag in a form field (after formatting by any previous sub-tags). It is used in conjunction with the Export to Form feature. The WebReport destination must be set to Form in order for SETFORM to have any effect. The field name identifies a column in the destination form to receive the data in the data tag. There needs to be a SETFORM sub-tag for each column of data that is to be set in the form. Each SETFORM sub-tag inserts data into the same record in the destination form until one of the following occurs, causing subsequent SETFORM sub-tags to write to the next record in destination form:

The NEXTROW parameter is used with the SETFORM sub-tag. This causes all subsequent SETFORM sub-tags to write to the next record in the form.
The reportview header section ends. This causes all subsequent SETFORM sub-tags (in the row section) to write to the next record in the form.
A new reportview row is started. As the row section is repeated for each row of data in the data source, each iteration of the row section also moves to the next record in the destination form.
The reportview row section ends. This causes any subsequent SETFORM sub-tags (in the footer) to write to the next record in the form.
The footer section ends.
Example usage: [LL_REPTAG=ENDDATE SETFORM:NEWDATE /]. In this case we are taking a column of data called ENDDATE from the data source and storing it in a field called NEWDATE which exists in the form we are exporting to. This sub-tag supports all standard Content Server types, so in the above example it is possible for ENDDATE to be an integer, string or date etc. A possible usage of this might involve using a CSV file as a WebReport data source and reading the content straight into a form. In addition to this, the source data could be in string format but we might, as an example, use TODATE to put a string into a Content Server date format before we use SETFORM to insert the data as a Content Server date type. E.g. [LL_REPTAG=ENDDATE TODATE:"%Y/%m/%d" SETFORM:NEWDATE /] will take a date from the data source formatted as YYYY/MM/DD and convert it to a Content Server date format that will be suitable for writing to the form.

Format	Description
SETFORM:<fieldname>	Populates a standard form field of any type.
SETFORM:<fieldname>:<rownum>	Populates the first field within a multi-value field if just fieldname is used. If the optional rownum operator is specified, the corresponding value within the multi-value field will be populated. For example SETFORM:'Address':6 will populate the sixth value of a multi-value field called 'Address'.
SETFORM:<setname>:<setnum>:<fieldname>	Populates a standard form field of any type within the specified set and set number. For example, SETFORM:'Documents':2:'Document Number' will populate the 'Document Number' field in set 2 of the 'Documents' set.
SETFORM:<setname>:<setnum>:<fieldname>:<rownum>	Populates the first field within a multi-value field within the specified set and set number if just fieldname is used. If the optional rownum operator is specified, the corresponding value within the multi-value field will be populated. For example SETFORM:'Documents':2:'Address':6 will populate the sixth value of a multi-value field called 'Address' in set 2 of the 'Documents' set.
Update Mode Syntax (Submission Mechanism)

In update mode (set when form is selected as a destination), if the form uses a submission mechanism then it is necessary to specify into which form record each set of data should be stored. The following rules govern how the target record is specified:

The target record in a form is determined with a sequence number (referred to as SEQ in these guidelines).
The SEQ to use for the current batch of SETFORM data can be set by using SETFORM:SEQ in a data tag that contains the required sequence number, e.g. [LL_REPTAG_"5" SETFORM:SEQ /] would result in the current set of data (as determined by other SETFORM sub-tags) being written to the form record which has a SEQ value of 5.
SETFORM:SEQ does not itself write any data to the form - it merely identfies a form record.
A tag containing SETFORM:SEQ must contain a positive integer in the main tag, otherwise the corresponding set of data will not be written to the form destination table.
The NEXTSEQ directive can be used if you want to update multiple Form records. The value in the data tag is used to set the next SEQ number to be used by any subsequent SETFORM sub-tags. This directive doesn't actually write any data to the destination form it is simply used to set the next SEQ to be used, e.g. [LL_REPTAG_"10" SETFORM:NEXTSEQ /] would determine that the next set of data will be written to the form record with SEQ number 10.
SETFORM:NEXTSEQ does not itself write any data to the form - it merely identifies a form record.
The NEXTKEY directive can be used to specify that the first record of data to be updated should match a particular key value (other than the SEQ column). If this directive is used, an additional sub-tag parameter is required to specify a field to be used for matching a key. For example, imagine that a form has a field called "fruit" and that the record with SEQ equal to 5 has a value of "apple" stored in the "fruit" field. The tag: [LL_REPTAG_"apple" SETFORM:NEXTKEY:fruit /] would effectively select the record with SEQ equal to 5 as the next record to be written to. In other words, the tag has specified that we want to write to the first record we find where the "fruit" field contains a value of "apple".
NEXTKEY currently only supports fields are not contained in sets.
If you are only updating some of the fields on a Form then the existing data will be retained.
Example 1:
[LL_REPTAG_'1' SETFORM:SEQ /]
[LL_REPTAG_'apple' SETFORM:fruit /]
[LL_REPTAG_'3' SETFORM:NEXTSEQ /]
[LL_REPTAG_'banana' SETFORM:fruit /]

This syntax will update two form records. It will change the values in the 'fruit' field to 'apple' for the record which has a SEQ value of 1, and 'banana' for the record which has a SEQ value of 3.

Example 2:
If a Form contained two fields, 'Fruit' and 'Country', and the form record which has a SEQ value of 1 contains values of 'raspberry' and 'France' respectively for these fields, the following syntax would set the value of 'Fruit' to 'apple' but is not setting a value for 'Country' so the value will remain as 'France' after the update.
[LL_REPTAG_'1' SETFORM:SEQ /]
[LL_REPTAG_'apple' SETFORM:fruit /]

Example 3:
[LL_REPTAG_'apple' SETFORM:NEXTKEY:fruit /]
[LL_REPTAG_'banana' SETFORM:fruit:NEXTROW /]
[LL_REPTAG_'orange' SETFORM:fruit /]

This syntax will find the first form record where the 'fruit' field contains 'apple', and change the value to 'banana'.
It will then update the 'fruit' field of the next form record and change the value to 'orange'.
For example, if the form record containing 'apple' had a SEQ value of 5, the NEXTROW directive would increment the SEQ value to 6.

SETFORM is one of a handful of specialized sub-tags that are called Action Sub-tags. Additional information on using this and other action sub-tags, can be found in the Advanced Information section: Action Sub-tags.

Update Mode Syntax (Revision Mechanism)

In update mode (set when form is selected as a destination), if the form uses a revision mechanism then it is only possible to add a new version of the form data. The NEXTROW, SEQ, NEXTSEQ and NEXTKEY arguments will have no effect. Just use SETFORM:<field details> to update the data.

See also: TODATE   

		
SETSHAREEXPIRY:<new expiry date>
This subtag updates the share expiry date for a valid Content Server node ID or node IDs that are shared. Valid date formats for the parameter include [LL_REPTAG_DATETIME /], [LL_REPTAG_DATE /], and Content Server formatted dates, for example 'Sat Apr 16 00:00:00 2011', 'Feb 20 2010', 'D/2012/12/25:00:00:00'.

If a specified node ID does not exist, an error is returned.

If a specified node ID is not shared, an error is returned.

The share expiry can only be set if the Content Server user who runs the WebReport has access control rights to view the permissions of the nodes.

Permissions are controlled by the settings in the Permission Page Access section on the Content Server Configure Access Control Admin page (func=admin.AccessControl).
If the setting is set to See Permissions, then the user only requires see permissions to set the list of share expiry dates.
If the setting is set to Edit Permissions, then the user requires edit permissions to set the list of share expiry dates.
		
