TIMESINCE:<ref date>:<precision>
This sub-tag expects a date in the main tag and returns the time delta (<ref date> - <main tag date>) in an easy-to-read format.
If no <ref date> is specified then the current date is used.
Negative values will be returned if the <ref date> is before the <main tag date>.
Dates must be specified in the following format:

'Mon dd YYYY' (Eg. 'Jan 12 2010')
'D/YYYY/mm/dd' (Eg. 'D/2009/12/14')
'DayOfWeek Mon dd hh:mm:ss YYYY' (Eg. 'Fri Jan 01 01:04:24 2010')
'YYYY-mm-dd hh:mm:ss' (Eg. '2038-01-19 03:14:07')
The main tag can also contain an integer representing a time interval in seconds. In this case, the <ref date> parameter is ignored and the value is returned in an easy-to-read format.

A second and optional parameter specifies how many units of precision to return. A default value of 2 is used when omitted.

Examples:

Tag	Output
[LL_REPTAG_'May 1 2010' TIMESINCE /]	11 months, 1 week
[LL_REPTAG_'May 1 2010' TIMESINCE:"May 2 2010" /]	1 day
[LL_REPTAG_'2011-05-01 00:00:00' TIMESINCE:'2011-05-01 01:01:23':3 /]	1 hour, 1 minute, 23 seconds
[LL_REPTAG_'3661' TIMESINCE /]	1 hour, 1 minute
[LL_REPTAG_'3661' TIMESINCE:3 /]	1 hour, 1 minute, 1 second
See also: DATE   TODATE   

		
TODATE:<format list>
This sub-tag converts string formatted date information into a Content Server format date. This means the output can be used in logical expressions such as to compare a custom date with a date parameter or possibly the current date. The output of TODATE can also be piped into the DATE sub-tag for further manipulation prior to display.

Modifier	Description
%%	A percentage sign
%b	The three-character abbreviated month name (e.g., Jan, Feb, etc.)
%d	The two-digit day of the month, from 01 to 31 (e.g., 01-31)
%m	The two-digit month (e.g., 01-12)
%p	AM or PM
%y	The two-digit year (e.g., 93)
%B	The full month name (e.g., January)
%H	The two-digit hour on a 24-hour clock, from 00 to 23
%I	The two-digit hour, from 01 through 12
%M	The minutes past the hour, from 00 to 59
%S	The seconds past the minute, from 00 to 59
%Y	The year, including the century (e.g., 1993)
Example of using TODATE with DATE to get from a custom date format to the Content Server short date format (Defined in the Content Server Admin pages):

Imagine you are starting with a custom date stored in the format: 2006-02-15T00:00:00. Use [LL_REPTAG=MY_DATE_COLUMN TODATE:"%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%S" /] to put the date into a string representation of a Content Server date. At this point the date will look like Wed Feb 15 00:00:00 2006 which may or may not be useful.

Now use the DATE sub-tag [LL_REPTAG=MY_DATE_COLUMN TODATE:"%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%S" DATE:SHORT /] to change the output so that the date is in the same format as, for example, the modified date in a Content Server folder browse. At this point the date might look like February 15, 2006 though this will depend on your system settings in the Admin pages

If the main tag is an integer and no parameters are passed to TODATE, then the sub-tag returns a date which is the epoch (1970-01-01 00:00:00) plus the value of the main tag.

See also: DATE   DATEINTEGER   LL_REPTAG_DATE   LL_REPTAG_DATETIME   

		
TOJSON
For a tag that returns an OSCRIPT type data structure, this tag converts the structure into a JSON (JavaScript Object Notation) structure that can be processed by a JavaScript interpreter. This sub-tag converts OSCRIPT structures as follows:

OSCRIPT Structure 	OSCRIPT Example	JSON Structure	JSON Example
INTEGER	12345	Primitive	12345
LONG	123456789000	Primitive	123456789000
REAL	.5	Primitive	0.5
STRING	"WebReports"	Primitive	'"WebReports"'
UNDEFINED	Undefined	Primitive	null
LIST	{'one','two'}	Array	["one","two"]
ASSOC	A<1,?,'one'=1,'two'=2>	Object	{"one":1, "two":2}
RECORD	R<'one'=1,'two'=2>	Object	{"one":1, "two":2}
RECARRAY	V{<'fruit','color'><'apple','green'><'banana','yellow'>}	Array of Objects	[{"fruit":"apple", "color":"green"}, {"fruit":"banana", "color":"yellow"}]
		
TOLIST:<delimiter>
TOLIST:<delimiter>:<index>
For a string which has a known delimiter (such as a comma), the string can be converted into a list. This list is similar to a programming array and is in the form: {1,2,3} or {'one','two','three'}. A list in this format can be used by the LIST and RANGE sub-tags; however, the TOLIST sub-tag also supports an optional index value that specifies which element in the newly created list to return.

The sub-tag can also operate on an Assoc or Record and returns a List containing the values stored in the specified structure. The delimiter parameter is ignored when the TOLIST sub-tag is used on such data types.

For example, if the first column of a data table returns the string: 'apple','orange','pear'; [LL_REPTAG_1 TOLIST:"," /] would return the list: {'apple','orange','pear'}

If the optional index parameter is also used, the syntax: [LL_REPTAG_1 TOLIST:",":2 /] would return the single element: orange

See also: LIST   RANGE   

		
TRIM
Removes all leading and trailing white space from the specified String. (White space is defined as any combination of spaces, form feeds, new lines, carriage returns, and horizontal or vertical tabs.)

		
TRUNC:<format>
Returns a truncated string.

Format	Description
TRUNC:<width>	Truncates the field to the number of characters specified in the width (starting from the first character).
TRUNC:<width>:<continuation characters>	Set continuation characters which will be appended to the return string to show that the data has been truncated. The length of the return string, including the continuation characters, will not exceed the value of the <width> argument unless the width value is less than the length of the continuation characters.
TRUNC:<width>:<continuation characters>:APPEND	Append continuation characters to the return string if the data has been truncated.
Examples:

[LL_REPTAG_'123456789' TRUNC:5 /] will return 12345

[LL_REPTAG_'123456789' TRUNC:5:"..." /] will return 12...

[LL_REPTAG_'123456789' TRUNC:5:"...":APPEND /] will return 12345...
		
TZOFFSET
Applies a time zone offset to dates. Date tags such as [LL_REPTAG_DATETIME /] and date columns [LL_REPTAG=CREATEDATE /] return the time at the server. TZOFFSET can be used to apply the appropriate time zone offset for the specific user viewing the output.

		
UNESCAPEJSON
Converts a specified string from an escaped JSON format. For example: If [LL_REPTAG_1 /] normally returns quote\u0022quote, [LL_REPTAG_1 UNESCAPEJSON /] will return: quote"quote. For more information on JSON escape characters see http://www.json.org.

		
UNESCAPESTR
Converts escaped characters to their equivalents.

		
UNESCAPEURL
Unescapes a previously escaped URL. The plus-sign character ("+") will be converted to a space and hexadecimal non-alphanumeric characters (represented by "%xx", where xx is hexadecimal notation) will be converted to their ASCII equivalent.

For example, [LL_REPTAG_"http%3A%2F%2Fjoe%2Efred%2Ecom" UNESCAPEURL /] would output http://joe.fred.com.

		
UPPER
Sets all text in the field to upper case.

		
URLTOPOST
For any valid URL, converts the "GET" form URL into a POST request by creating a series of appropriately named FORM fields with corresponding values. If the URL contains a prefix (prior to any parameters) the prefix is abandoned and only the parameters are converted into form fields.

For example, the following URL: /cs/cs.exe?func=ll&objId=157220&objAction=RunReport&reqcacheid=1005851343 converts into the following lines of HTML:

<INPUT TYPE="HIDDEN" NAME="func" VALUE="ll">
<INPUT TYPE="HIDDEN" NAME="objId" VALUE="157220">
<INPUT TYPE="HIDDEN" NAME="objAction" VALUE="RunReport">
<INPUT TYPE="HIDDEN" NAME="reqcacheid" VALUE="1005851343">
		
