WFDBLOOKUP:<table ref>:<column ref>
WFDBLOOKUP:<table ref>:<column ref>:<column select>
WFDBLOOKUP:<table ref>:<column ref>:<column select>:MULTIMATCH
This sub-tag is used to lookup data from any database table created by the Content Server WebForms module. It expects a valid key to be supplied by the data tag and accepts parameters to specify the appropriate table and column to reference. The key, table and column information are then used to lookup one or more rows from the specified WebForms table. An additional parameter can also be included to specify a particular column of data to be returned. If more than one column is returned, the data is provided in an OSCRIPT RECARRAY structure (proprietary Content Server data structure). This RECARRAY structure can be dereferenced using the RECARRAY sub-tag or converted into JSON format using a TOJSON sub-tag. If only one match is found, the RECARRAY will only have one record but if more than one row of data is returned, the data is provided in multiple records within the RECARRAY structure.

The <table ref> parameter can be either: a form template ID or a form ID. Either of these objects are used to determine the correct SQL table name. Note that the user running the WebReport must have the appropriate level of permissions to be able to "See Contents" on the form/template objects. The <column ref> is an identifier that specifies the name of a column where the key will be searched for. The optional <column select> parameter is used to narrow the data returned from the query down to a single, specific column.

Normally if only one column is being returned, this sub-tag only returns the most recently added item in a single field of text, i.e. not in a RECARRAY; however, the MULTIMATCH option allows more than one row of data to be returned, even though only one column has been selected. If no column has been selected, the data is always returned in a RecArray structure. This structure can be dereferenced using the RECARRAY sub-tag or the TOJSON sub-tag can be used to convert the structure into JSON format (the client can use this to create JavaScript variables).

The various methods of returning data are described in the following bullets. Generally speaking a RECARRAY is always returned unless a column select has been specified without a MULTIMATCH option (which results in a single text field).

If the column select option has not been specified, all columns for the data source are returned for as many rows as are matched by the query
If the column select option has been specified, only the data for the specified column in the first matched row is returned
If the column select option has been specified as well as the option called MULTIMATCH, then only the specified column is returned for any matched rows. This option allows for more than one row of data but the data is always returned in a RECARRAY, even if only one row is found
See also: RECARRAY   TOJSON   

		
WFESIGNINFO:<option>
This sub-tag will return information associated with a valid eSign workflow task.

The data tag for the CONFIRMUSERS and DOCS options must contain a list containing the workflow eSign task's workid, subworkid and taskid, e.g. [LL_REPTAG_'{workid, subworkid, taskid}' /].
The data tag for the other options is ignored and can be blank.

Format	Description
WFESIGNINFO:ADDITIONALPASSWORD	
Returns a String indicating the Signing Password Required eSign settings:

"Y" if the "Yes" Signing Password Required checkbox is checked and Additional Password is selected.
"N" if the "Yes" Signing Password Required checkbox is checked and Alternate Password is selected.
"S" if the Signing Password Required checkbox is not checked.
WFESIGNINFO:CONFIG	Returns an Assoc containing the eSign configuration settings.
WFESIGNINFO:CONFIRMUSER:<systemPassword>:<signingPassword>(:<timezone>)	
Verifies whether or not the User executing the subtag is verified to Approve or Reject the step. If the system does not require one of the passwords, the corresponding parameter can be left blank. Example: If the system only requires signing passwords, leave the <systemPassword> parameter blank: WFESIGNINFO:CONFIRMUSER:"":"[LL_REPTAG_&signPassword /]"

The optional <timezone> parameter should be a String indicating the users timezone, as set in eSign configuration. Example: "Eastern Daylight Time".

Returns a signing token if the verification was successful or an error message if the verification was unsuccessful.

As this tag handles sensitive information, it's best not to hard-code the passwords while using this sub-tag as any user that can edit the report would be able to see the password. Instead, it's best to pass these values as parameters over a secure protocol like https.

WFESIGNINFO:DOCS	Returns a String with the name of the document under review for Approval/Rejection.
WFESIGNINFO:TIMEZONES	Returns a List containing the TimeZone options for eSign based on whether the system is configured to allow for user, client, or server timezones. The raw options for these settings can be retrieved using the WFESIGNINFO:CONFIG.
See also: LIST   WFTASKINFO   

		
WFFORM:<parms>
Return information about the workflow form fields associated with a specific workflow (SUBWORKID). This sub-tag supports both sets and multi-value fields through use of the MV and SET operators.

For example: [LL_REPTAG=SUBWORKID WFFORM: <formname>:<fieldname> :DISPLAY /] will return the field value stored in the form <formname> and the field <fieldname> for any field type. If <fieldname> is a multi-value field or an set a comma-separated list of values will be returned.

Syntax	Description
WFFORM:<formname>:<fieldname>	Will return TRUE/FALSE depending on whether a field, <fieldname>, exists with a non-blank value in the form, <formname>. If a set is specified in <fieldname>, a single entry in any one of the set's field values will cause this to return TRUE. If <fieldname> is a multi-value field, a single entry in any one will also cause this to return TRUE. <fieldname> can also be nested within a set either as a regular field or a multi-value field.
WFFORM: <formname> : <fieldname> :DISPLAY	Will return the value in the field, <fieldname> , for the form, <formname> . If <fieldname> is a set or a multi-value field a comma-separated list of values will be returned.
WFFORM: <formname> : <fieldname> :ID	Will return the ID of the field, <fieldname> , for the form, <formname> if it is present. If <fieldname> exists inside a set, it will be returned if no field matching <fieldname> exists at the top level in the form. If <fieldname> exists at the top level of the form and within a set of the same form, the field ID at the top level (not within the set) will take precedence.
WFFORM: <formname> : <fieldname> : <fieldval>	Will return TRUE/FALSE depending on whether a field, <fieldname> , exists with a value equal to <fieldval> in the form, <formname> . <fieldname> may be a field within a set (including a multi-value), or any element within a multi-value field.
WFFORM: <formname> :MV: <fieldname> :COUNT
Will return number of multi-value fields in use.
WFFORM: <formname> :MV: <fieldname> : <n>
Will return TRUE/FALSE for the presence of a specific non-blank element in a multi-value field, <fieldname> , for the form, <formname> at the index location <n> . The value of <n> must be a positive integer between 1 and n where n does not exceed the length of the multi-value field. If n exceeds the length of the multi-value field, an empty string will be returned.
WFFORM: <formname> :MV: <fieldname> : <n> : <fieldval>
Will return TRUE/FALSE for the presence of <fieldval> in a multi-value field, <fieldname> , for the form, <formname> at the index location <n> . The value of <n> must be a positive integer between 1 and n where n does not exceed the length of the multi-value field.
WFFORM: <formname> :MV: <fieldname> : <n> :DISPLAY	Will return the value in the multi-value field, <fieldname> , for the form, <formname> at the index location < n> where < n> is a positive integer between 1 and n. The value of <n> must be a positive integer between 1 and n where n does not exceed the length of the multi-value field.
WFFORM: <formname> :MV: <fieldname> :INDEX: <fieldval>	Will return the first index of the multi-value field, <fieldname> , for the form, <formname> where <fieldval> is equal to the value contained in the multi-value field at index. For example, if <fieldval> exists in the third element of <fieldname> , the number 3 will be returned.
WFFORM: <formname> :MV: <setname> : COUNT	Will return the number of multi-value sets in use.
WFFORM: <formname> :SET: <setname> : <fieldname>	Uses the SET operator allowing field sets to be explicitly referenced. This example will return TRUE if field, <fieldname> within set , <setname> is non-blank . Only fields within <setname> can be referenced so if <fieldname> exists outside the set, it will not be found. If <fieldname> is a multi-value field, TRUE will be returned if any field within it is non-blank.
WFFORM: <formname> :SET: <setname> : <fieldname> :DISPLAY	Will return the value in the field, <fieldname> , for the form, <formname> , if <fieldname> is a field within <setname>. If <fieldname> is a multi-value field, a comma-separated list of the defined values will be returned. If no defined value exists, either in a multi-value field, or a standard field, an empty list will be returned.
WFFORM: <formname> :SET: <setname> : <fieldname> :ID	Will return the ID of the field <fieldname> within the set <setname>. If <fieldname> exists outside <setname> it will not be returned. <fieldname> can be either a regular or multi-value field.
WFFORM: <formname> :SET: <setname> : <fieldname> : <fieldval>	Will return TRUE/FALSE depending on whether a field, <fieldname> , exists with a value equal to <fieldval> in the set, <setname> . If <fieldname> is a multi-value field, all elements will be checked for equality against <fieldval> , if any match, TRUE will be returned.
WFFORM: <formname> :SET: <setname> :MV: <fieldname> :COUNT	Will return number of multi-value fields that have been populated.
WFFORM: <formname> :SET: <setname> :MV: <fieldname> : <n>	Will return TRUE/FALSE for the presence of a specific non-blank element in a multi-value field, <fieldname> , within a set, for the form, <formname> at the index location <n> . The value of <n> must be a positive integer between 1 and n where n does not exceed the length of the multi-value field.
WFFORM: <formname> :SET: <setname> :MV: <fieldname> : <n> : <fieldval>	Will return TRUE/FALSE for the presence of <fieldval> in a multi-value field, <fieldname> , within a set, for the form, <formname> at the index location <n> . The value of <n> must be a positive integer between 1 and n where n does not exceed the length of the multi-value field.
WFFORM: <formname> :SET: <setname> :MV: <fieldname> : <n> :DISPLAY	Will return the value in the multi-value field, <fieldname> , within a set, for the form, <formname> at the index location < n> where < n> is a positive integer between 1 and n. The value of <n> must be a positive integer between 1 and n where n does not exceed the length of the multi-value field.
WFFORM: <formname> :SET: <setname> :MV: <fieldname> :INDEX: <fieldval>	Will return the first index of the multi-value field, <fieldname> , within a set, for the form, <formname> where <fieldval> is equal to the value contained in the multi-value field at index.
WFFORM: <formname> :MVSET: <setname> : <n> : <fieldname>	Will return TRUE or FALSE where the multi-value set, <setname> , has a non-blank field, <fieldname> , at the index location < n >, within the form, <formname> .
WFFORM: <formname> :MVSET: <setname> : <n> : <fieldname> :DISPLAY	Will display the value of a field <fieldname> within a multi-value set, <setname> at the index location < n >, within the form, <formname> .
WFFORM: <formname> :MVSET: <setname> : <n> : <fieldname> :ID	Will display the ID of a field <fieldname> within a multi-value set, <setname> at the index location < n >, within the form, <formname> .
WFFORM: <formname> :MVSET: <setname> : <n> : <fieldname> : <fieldval>	Will return TRUE or FALSE where the multi-value set, <setname> , has a field, <fieldname> , at the index location < n >, within the form, <formname> that is equal to the value specified in <attval> .
WFFORM: <formname> :MVSET: <setname> : <n> :MV: <fieldname> :COUNT	Returns the number of multi-value fields in use in the multi-value set.
WFFORM: <formname> :MVSET: <setname> : <n> :MV: <fieldname> :< m >	Will return TRUE or FALSE where the multi-value set, <setname> , at index location <n> has a multi-value field, <fieldname> , at the index location < m >, that is non-blank.
WFFORM: <formname> :MVSET: <setname> : <n> :MV: <fieldname> :< m >:DISPLAY	Will display the value of an multi-value field <fieldname> , at the index location < m >, within a multi-value set, <setname> at the index location < n >, within the form, <formname> .
WFFORM: <formname> :MVSET: <setname> : <n> :MV: <fieldname> :< m >: <fieldval>	Will return TRUE or FALSE where the multi-value set, <setname> , at the index location < n >, has a multi-value-field, <fieldname> , at the index location < m > whose value is equal to the value specified in <attval> .
WFFORM: <formname> :MVSET: <setname> : <n> :MV: <fieldname> :INDEX: <fieldval>	Will return the first index of the multi-value field, <fieldname> , within a multi-value set, for the form, <formname> where <fieldval> is equal to the value contained in the multi-value field at index.
		
